
INSERT INTO scripts (category, stage, target_audience, script_role, sort_order, tags, versions)
VALUES
(
  'prospecting',
  'Warm Outreach – Direct Approach (Existing Clients)',
  'clients',
  'consultant',
  910,
  ARRAY['warm-market', 'direct', 'existing-client', 'investment', 'whatsapp', 'jana-prospecting'],
  '[{"title": "Direct Approach — Existing Client (Jana)", "author": "Jana (Auctus)", "content": "# Warm Outreach – Direct Approach\n**Best for:** Existing clients you already have a relationship with\n\n---\n\n## The Script\n\nHi [Name]! Hope you are having a great start to [Year]!\n\nI know you mentioned that you want to focus on [their current savings/investment plan]. Just checking if you would be open to having a quick look at our new [product/fund] as a possible option to diversify?\n\n---\n\n## Why This Works\n\n- Opens with genuine warmth and a personal touch\n- References a previous conversation to show you listen and remember\n- Frames it as an option, not a hard sell\n- The word diversify appeals to financially-aware clients\n- Low-pressure: just checking if you would be open gives them an easy out\n\n---\n\n## Key Principles\n\n- **Recall their goals** — mention what they told you last time\n- **One product at a time** — keep the ask focused\n- **Give them control** — suggest Zoom or a meeting time that suits them\n- **No pressure language** — avoid words like must, should, or urgency tactics\n\n---\n\n## Tips from Jana\n\n> For existing clients, I go straight to the point but always reference something they shared with me before. It shows I was paying attention and makes the outreach feel personal, not transactional."}]'::jsonb
),
(
  'prospecting',
  'Warm Outreach – Soft Approach (Warm Market / Community Contacts)',
  'warm-market',
  'consultant',
  920,
  ARRAY['warm-market', 'soft', 'community', 'whatsapp', 'non-pushy', 'jana-prospecting'],
  '[{"title": "Soft Approach — Warm Market / Community (Jana)", "author": "Jana (Auctus)", "content": "# Warm Outreach – Soft Approach\n**Best for:** Friends, community members, church mates, social circle — people you know but have not spoken to professionally\n\n---\n\n## The Script\n\nHi [Name]! Hope all is well on your end. :)\n\nI just thought of asking — are you currently working with any financial consultant for your planning needs?\n\nIf not, or if you are open to exploring, I would love to see if we can work together. I have been working with some of our [community/group] friends for years now. They have entrusted me with their financial planning and I am truly blessed to be part of their journey.\n\nNo pressure at all — I just thought of reaching out to see if you would be open for a quick sharing. :)\n\n---\n\n## Why This Works\n\n- Starts with a question, not a pitch — far less intimidating\n- Asking if they currently work with anyone is non-threatening and opens dialogue naturally\n- Social proof via community builds credibility through shared identity\n- No pressure at all explicitly removes the awkwardness of being sold to\n- Ends with a light, open invitation — not a close\n\n---\n\n## Key Principles\n\n- **Lead with a question** — let them volunteer their current situation\n- **Social proof from shared community** — mention mutual friends or group members (with permission)\n- **Never assume they need help** — frame it as exploration\n- **One ask only** — just ask if they are open, do not jump to scheduling in message 1\n\n---\n\n## Tips from Jana\n\n> For warm market contacts — especially community or church friends — I never lead with a product. I lead with curiosity about their situation. The moment they say they do not have anyone yet or they are open to exploring, that is your green light."}]'::jsonb
),
(
  'prospecting',
  'Warm Outreach – Curiosity Approach (DIY Investors / Existing FA Contacts)',
  'warm-market',
  'consultant',
  930,
  ARRAY['warm-market', 'curiosity', 'diy-investor', 'portfolio-review', 'no-pressure', 'jana-prospecting'],
  '[{"title": "Curiosity Approach — DIY Investors / Existing FA Contacts (Jana)", "author": "Jana (Auctus)", "content": "# Warm Outreach – Curiosity Approach\n**Best for:** Contacts who are financially savvy, already self-managing investments, or have an existing FA\n\n---\n\n## The Script\n\nI get you, and I honestly respect that you are very hands-on with your finances. That shows how intentional you are with your financial planning — especially with insurance, tax-saving plans, and dividend investing.\n\nDo you have someone helping you with all of these? :)\n\nWhat I usually do in situations like this is a one-time portfolio assessment — just to spot any blind spots, overlaps, or things that might be worth a second look. No harm in checking.\n\nIf it sounds useful, we can have a chill chat over coffee or tea. Up to you. :)\n\n---\n\n## Why This Works\n\n- Leads with a genuine compliment — validates their effort without making them feel inadequate\n- Reframes the ask — not a sales pitch, but an offer to check if everything is optimised\n- Blind spots is a powerful word — it implies there could be gaps without being insulting\n- Low commitment ask — a chill chat over tea feels very different from a formal consultation\n- Up to you returns control to them, reducing resistance\n\n---\n\n## When to Use This\n\n- Contact mentions they already have an FA\n- Contact seems financially independent or handles their own investments\n- Contact brushes off financial conversations as already sorted\n\n---\n\n## Key Principles\n\n- **Never compete with their current FA** — position yourself as a second opinion, not a replacement\n- **Portfolio assessment framing** — one-time, low-pressure, no commitment\n- **Casual setting** — suggest tea, coffee, or a quick Zoom, never a formal presentation\n\n---\n\n## Tips from Jana\n\n> When someone says they already have an FA or manage their own investments, that is not a dead end. I offer a one-time portfolio review — not to replace anyone, just to give them a fresh set of eyes. Most people are open to a second opinion when you take the pressure off."}]'::jsonb
),
(
  'prospecting',
  'Warm Outreach – Event Follow-Up & Nurture (Lifestyle Prospecting)',
  'warm-market',
  'consultant',
  940,
  ARRAY['warm-market', 'event-follow-up', 'lifestyle-prospecting', 'door-gift', 'nurture', 'jana-prospecting'],
  '[{"title": "Event Follow-Up — Missed the Event (Jana)", "author": "Jana (Auctus)", "content": "# Event Follow-Up – Missed the Event\n**Best for:** Contacts you invited to a lifestyle event (fitness class, lunch, gathering) who could not make it\n\n---\n\n## The Script\n\nHi [Name]! Hope you are feeling much better now!\n\nI am sorry you could not make it to the [event name] — we missed you there!\n\nI actually had a personalised door gift prepared for you, so I would still love to pass it to you. Let me know when it is convenient and I can meet you at [location]!\n\nAlso, while we catch up, I can briefly share about a new [product/fund] that was recently launched — thought it might be something you would find interesting as well. Let me know if this week or next works better for you. :)\n\n---\n\n## Why This Works\n\n- The door gift is a brilliant non-salesy reason to meet in person — creates genuine goodwill\n- Briefly share softens the business pitch — it is secondary to the catch-up\n- Giving two time options makes it easy to say yes\n- The entire message feels like care, not selling\n\n---\n\n## Key Principles\n\n- **Events create warmth** — always follow up within 48 hours\n- **The gift creates reciprocity** — it opens doors without being transactional\n- **Business is secondary** — lead with the relationship and the gift, not the product\n\n---\n\n## Jana Prospecting System\n\n> I attend one social event per month to meet new people. I also run lifestyle events like fitness classes that allow natural, non-transactional connections. The door gift strategy is key — it gives me a genuine reason to follow up with people who could not make it.\n\n**Weekly schedule:**\n- Monday and Friday: Dedicated prospecting blocks\n- Daily: Small consistent outreach habit\n- One Saturday per month: Social events or gatherings\n- Quarterly: COI (Centre of Influence) meet-ups"}, {"title": "Nurture Follow-Up — Long-Lost Contact (Jana)", "author": "Jana (Auctus)", "content": "# Nurture Follow-Up – Reconnecting with Old Contacts\n**Best for:** Contacts you have not spoken to in a while who reach out or resurface\n\n---\n\n## The Script\n\nHi [Name]! Happy New Year! It has been forever — hope you are well!\n\n*(Wait for their reply. If they bring up finances or life goals, respond warmly:)*\n\nThank you for trusting me with this. That is actually a great mindset already — wanting to be wiser with your finances.\n\n[Amount] is a good starting point, and we can definitely explore options that fit your goals and comfort level.\n\nWould you be able to meet for a consultation sometime next week? Let me know which day works and we will take it from there. :)\n\n---\n\n## Why This Works\n\n- Responding warmly to their initiative removes all pressure — you are just following their lead\n- Starting point framing validates small amounts and makes it feel achievable, not embarrassing\n- Asking about a specific day creates momentum without being pushy\n\n---\n\n## Key Principles\n\n- **Do not pitch first** — let them bring up the topic\n- **Validate any amount** — never make someone feel their budget is too small\n- **Keep it light** — this is a consultation, not a close\n\n---\n\n## Tips from Jana\n\n> The best leads often come from people who reach out to you. Stay warm and consistent with your network, and when they are ready, they will find you."}]'::jsonb
);
